column1: ## pLI scores closer to one indicate more intolerance to protein-truncating variation. For a set of transcripts
## intolerant of protein-truncating variation, we suggest pLI â‰¥ 0.9.
## The constraint score shown in gnomAD is the ratio of the observed / expected (oe) number of loss-of-function variants
## in that gene. The expected counts are based on a mutational model that takes sequence context, coverage and methylation
## Observed/expected (oe) is a continuous measure of how tolerant a gene is to a certain class of variation
## (e.g. loss-of-function). When a gene has a low oe value, it is under stronger selection for that class of variation
## than a gene with a higher value. Because counts depend on gene size and sample size, the precision of the oe values
## varies a lot from one gene to the next. Therefore in addition to the oe value, we also display the 90% confidence
## interval (CI) for each of the oe values. When evaluating how constrained a gene is, it is essential to take the 90%
## Although oe is a continuous value, we understand that it can be useful to use a threshold for certain applications. In
## particular, for the interpretation of Mendelian diseases cases, we suggest using the upper bound of the oe CI < 0.35
## as a threshold if needed. Again, ideally oe should be used as a continuous value rather than a cutoff and evaluating
## the oe 90% CI is a must.
